<HEADLINE>
<P>
A BOWL FULL OF BASKETS OF DELIGHTS; 
</P>
<P>
68TH SEASON'S OPENING NIGHT IS FIRST CLASS ALL THE WAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY LOU LOPER, Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There are some things that improve with age: The Hollywood Bowl is one. Tuesday 
night was heaven. For the opening night of the 68th Bowl season, the skies were 
friendly -- only one helicopter. As twilight took its sweet time about becoming 
night, the silhouette of lined up trees on the hill behind the bowl was a 
painting worthy of Sotheby's. 
</P>
<P>
It was all first class. The official Steinway. Schramsberg champagne. Beluga 
caviar. Lobster bisque. Silver goblets. Blue Willow china. The green wicker 
picnic baskets that everyone used to get with Blue Chip Stamps scattered 
throughout the Garden and Terrace box areas. 
</P>
<P>
And there was Nancy Reagan in Box 1131. A memorable Tchaikovsky finale 
conducted by Yuri Temirkanov. Orrin Howard's program notes. Polite parking 
attendants. 
</P>
<P>
Was it going well? "When hasn't it?" Philharmonic executive director Ernest 
Fleischmann quipped, noting that Russian emigre Vladimir Feltsman would be 
starring as pianist in Beethoven's Concerto No. 4 in G, and that Feltsman's 
wife, Anna, had the artist's box. 
</P>
<P>
That was Box 1131, where the lookouts were posted waiting for Nancy Reagan. She 
and son Ron Reagan and his wife, Doria, were the special guests of the 
Feltsmans because of aid in getting them out of the Soviet Union. "For us, they 
are the best people; we love them," Anna said, throwing her arms around Nancy 
Reagan. (Former President Ronald Reagan was in Anaheim, co-announcing the 
All-Star game with Vin Scully.) 
</P>
<P>
In their corner box, where they hosted Dody and Otis Booth, Carol and Mike 
Inman spread black and white plaid place mats, flew black and white balloons 
and set their hook-on trays with herb bouquets and white narcissus. 
</P>
<P>
It took both Judy and Steaven Jones to carry the load of their green hamper 
filled with goodies Judy had concocted from recipes in the Los Angeles Junior 
League Cookbook. Daryn and Bill Horton were waiting for them with "a little 
Schramsberg." 
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, Colette and Charles Witt had pate from the Biltmore Hotel out for 
Louise and Tom Jones. Maury and Carolyn De Wald and Carla and Rudy Rehm were 
eating Brie before the beef tenderloin and lemon bars. Dee and Bob Wilson set 
up blue agapanthus and red and white roses for Gretchen and George Gibbs before 
presenting Veuve Clicquot. 
</P>
<P>
Brian Panosian wore his yellow suspenders and sat in the $4 top-row seats (the 
better to see the stars), dropping by twice to see his parents, Vera (chairman 
of the Hollywood Bowl Volunteers) and Howard Panosian in their box. 
</P>
<P>
Marian and Stanley Brown had moved that day into the Mirabella condos on 
Wilshire. But the Bowl, with Terry and Diane Mullin as their regular opening 
night guests, is a tradition. The picnic went on. 
</P>
<P>
Speaking of tradition, Norma and David McIntyre always serve lobster bisque; 
enjoying were Janice and Bob Carpenter. 
</P>
<P>
Where did she want to go for her 19th birthday? Lindsey Kozberg said the Bowl, 
and parents Joanne and Roger Kozberg obliged, bringing along Andrea Van de 
Kamp, whose husband, John, was off campaigning for governor. 
</P>
<P>
Alan (he's Philharmonic board secretary) and Nancy Wayte opened the Bristol 
Farms chervil chicken for Judge William and Julie Masterson. 
</P>
<P>
The Bowl calls for a best effort. Whitley Collins did just that. He invited 
John Roberts, Hayden Eaves and Scott Kerslake to sit in his parents' box. With 
youthful gusto, they chowed down on sandwiches. 
</P>
<P>
RELATED STORY: Calendar, Page 1 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Nancy Reagan, center, relaxes with friends and family at the Hollywood 
Bowl's opening night picnic. With her are, from left, Anna Feltsman, Doria and 
Ron Reagan and Sergei Petrov. JAYNE KAMIN-ONCEA / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
