<HEADLINE>
<P>
EASY RIDING MARKS TOUR AS CYCLISTS GEAR FOR THE ALPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MONTPELLIER, France 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A long ride in the southern French countryside by Tour de France cyclists 
produced little change as Laurent Fignon of France and Greg LeMond of the 
United States remained 1-2 today in the standings after the 12th stage. 
</P>
<P>
The tedium of group riding was broken only by a small demonstration in a town 
about 12 miles from the finish. About a dozen people protesting the location of 
garbage dumps in the area put some trees and rocks on a narrow passage on the 
cyclists' route. 
</P>
<P>
Roadside fans helped officials clear away the barricades, but a television 
reporter was punched by one of the demonstrators, and the main pack of riders 
had to stop briefly. 
</P>
<P>
There were no serious delays, however, and the results of today's 150-mile race 
from Toulouse to Montpellier were unaltered by the incident. 
</P>
<P>
Italians Valerio Tebaldi and Giancarlo Perini and Frenchman Dominique Arnaud 
escaped early and gradually built up a 20-minute advantage over the rest of the 
group. 
</P>
<P>
Tebaldi eventually won in a sprint over Perini in 5 hours, 40 minutes, 54 
seconds with Arnaud third, more than two minutes back. 
</P>
<P>
The rest of the field -- including Fignon in 25th position and LeMond in 46th 
-- trailed by more than 21 minutes, and two-time Tour winner Fignon maintained 
his 7-second advantage over LeMond, the 1986 champion. 
</P>
<P>
The overall standings were left unchanged among the leaders as the group seemed 
to be conserving its strength for the Alps. 
</P>
<P>
The men's race is a 2,020-mile counterclockwise journey around France, ending 
in Paris on July 23. 
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Olympic champion Monique Knol of the Netherlands took the second 
stage of the women's Tour de France today to retain the lead. She holds a 
17-second lead in the overall standings over two-time champion Jeannie Longo of 
France. 
</P>
<P>
American Susan Elias is now third, 35 seconds back. 
</P>
<P>
The women's Tour this year is shorter than usual but has more mountain climbs. 
It is 482 miles long and has 11 stages, ending just before the men's Tour in 
Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Valerio Tebaldi raises arm in victory as he crosses finish line in 
Montpellier to win the 12th stage of the Tour de France. Reuters 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
